(Advanced) Quest 10: Capstone Project - NFT Marketplace SC
Introduction
In the previous quest, we built a simple memory card game and minted Non-Fungible Tokens (NFTs). However, more functionalities can be utilized with NFTs!
In this quest, we will be moving on to the next section of our Capstone project, building an NFT marketplace! This marketplace will be powered by two underlying smart contracts - an auction smart contract and an auction manager smart contract. In this marketplace, players of the game that managed to mint NFTs can list their NFTs up for auction and sellers can come in and bid for them.

For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #avalanche-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to: 
  • Describe what Decentralized Finance is
  • Be familiar with advanced Solidity concepts
  • Create smart contracts that facilitate the auctioning of NFTs
  • Describe how smart contracts interact with one another

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Introduction to Decentralized Finance
Decentralized Finance, or more commonly known by its acronym, DeFi, is a term you commonly hear being thrown around in Web3. But what is DeFi? Essentially, DeFi is a financial technology based on public blockchains. DeFi allows people or businesses to conduct financial transactions like lending, trading or making payments to another user via blockchain technology. 
There are many advantages with the use of DeFi compared to its traditional counterpart, the Centralized Finance (CeFi). In CeFi, banks act as the third party to facilitate money transfers between parties and charge fees for the use of their service. DeFi on the other hand eliminates the need for a third party to conduct financial transactions.  

DeFi, with the use of blockchain technology and smart contracts, provides both security and transparency. Completed transactions are recorded on the blockchain for anyone to see without revealing the identity of the parties involved. With DeFi, you can check all the accounts, liquidity, positions and liabilities of organisations as all this information is available on-chain. 

This is in stark contrast to CeFi, which is opaque - which essentially leaves you with no choice but to trust the individuals running the organisation, which is the antithesis of crypto. As recent events have demonstrated to the world, this is definitely a point of paramount importance and a situation we want to avoid.

With CeFi, given how centralized it is, if the servers go down, users will not be able to use the service and cannot make any transactions. DeFi eliminates a single point of failure, as the transactions are stored on distributed ledgers. 

Article: What is Decentralized Finance and How does it Work?

Learning Checklist
  • DeFi is an emerging financial technology based on secure distributed ledgers
  • DeFi eliminates intermediaries by allowing people, merchants, and businesses to conduct financial transactions through emerging technology
  • Anyone with an internet connection can access a DeFi platform to make transactions  DeFi enables any two parties to directly negotiate interest rates and lend money via DeFi networks

Step 4: Auction.sol - Variables & Constructor()
Under the contracts folder, open up the Auction.sol file. Firstly, we will take a look at the variables declared from line 8 to 22. 

These are the variables that we’ll be using for our auction smart contract. The variables are referenced from functions created in the code below. 

  • endTime is the end timestamp of the auction. The auction will end if the current timestamp is equal or greater than the endTime
  • startTime is the timestamp that marks the start of the auction
  • maxBid prefers the current max bid amount
  • maxBidder is the address of the max bidder
  • creator is the address of the auction creator
  • bids is an array of collection of bids
  • tokenId is the id of the token that has been auctioned
  • isCancelled will be true if the auction has been cancelled
  • isDirectBuy will be true if someone placed a bid with a higher or equal value than the direct buy price
  • minIncrement is the minimum increment for the bid
  • directBuyPrice is the price for a direct buy, a token will be transferred to the bidder and bidding will stop
  • startPrice is the starting price for the auction
  • nftAddress is the address of the NFT contract
  • _nft refers to the NFT token


In line 24 to 29, we define the variable AuctionState of type enum with four different auction states - ‘OPEN’, ‘CANCELLED’, ‘ENDED’ and ‘DIRECT_BUY’. Enums restrict a variable to have one of only a few user-defined values. The use of enums is to reduce the number of bugs in your code as it makes code easier to read and maintain. 


Next, a struct object is defined in line 31 to 35. It contains the address of the bidder and the amount that the user bids. Structs in Solidity allow you to create more complicated data types that have multiple properties. You can define your own struct with the struct keyword.


Now let’s take a look at the constructor() function. In Solidity, a constructor() is declared inside of a smart contract and it is a special function that invokes only once when the contract is deployed. The main use of our constructor() function here was to initialise contract states.
Step 5: Auction.sol - allBids()
We will now be looking at all the functions in the Auction smart contract. 

The first function we’ll be looking at is allBids(). The main purpose of this function is to retrieve a list of all current bid amounts and the addresses of the bidders. 

This function has been given the visibility modifiers of external and view. As a recap, external functions are functions that can be called by other contracts and view functions can only retrieve a value, not modify any contract states.

In the body of the function, two arrays are initialized - addrs and bidPrice. The size of the arrays are based on the current number of bids stored, which can be retrieved using the .length function. A for loop is then used to assign values from the bids array to addrs and bidPrice accordingly.
Step 6: Auction.sol - placeBids()

The next function we’ll be looking at is placeBid(). Essentially, this function allows users to place bids in auctions.

The first thing we do in this function is to declare certain requirements that need to be met before a user is allowed to place a bid. One way we can do this in Solidity is with the require keyword. These are the following requirements that we’ll be declaring:
  • Line 76 - there cannot be more than 5 bidders allowed for an auction
  • Line 77 - the auction creator cannot place a bid
  • Line 78 - the auction state needs to be opened before a bid can be be placed
  • Line 79 - the bid submitted must be larger than the starting price set by auction creator
  • Line 80 - the bid submitted must be higher than the current highest bid and minimum increment set by the auction creator

After all requirements are met, the contract retrieves the previous highest bidder lastHighestBidder and previous highest bid amount lastHighestBid. This is so that it can later refund the previous bid to the previous highest bidder. The new highest bid amount maxBid and new highest bidder maxBidder are set. 

A check is then done to see if the current bid is more than or equals to directBuyPrice. If it fulfils the condition, isDirectBuy is set to true and the auction ends. In line 90, the contract adds the new bid to the list of existing bids.

In lines 92 to 95, it refunds the previous bid to the previous highest bidder (provided there was an existing bid). The NewBid event is emitted at line 97. Finally, a boolean value true is returned as a bid has been successfully placed. 
Step 7: Auction.sol - withdrawToken()

Next, we move on to the withdrawToken() function. You’ll notice that this function is empty, that’s because you’ll be filling up the code for this one! Not to worry, we’ll be breaking down the sequence of events step by step based on the comments left in the code.

Firstly, let's set some requirements in order for this function to be called. We need to check if the auction has ended or if a direct buy is triggered. A direct buy happens when someone bids an amount set by the auction creator, usually a high amount which results in the auction ending and the item being sold directly to the bidder. 

require(getAuctionState() == AuctionState.ENDED || getAuctionState() == AuctionState.DIRECT_BUY);

The code segment above calls the getAuctionState() function and checks the current state of the auction to ensure that either auction has ended or the direct buy clause is triggered. Add the code above to the function.
 
require(msg.sender == maxBidder);

The second condition we’ll need to add is to ensure only the person who makes the highest bid can withdraw the token, we can check for this by comparing the wallet addresses. Add the code above to the function as well.

_nft.transferFrom(address(this), maxBidder, tokenId);

If the two conditions have passed, we will transfer the token over to the highest bidder based on token id using the transferFrom() functionality. Add the code above to the function.

emit WithdrawToken(maxBidder);

Lastly, we will emit an event to broadcast that this particular user has withdrawn the token from the Auction. Add the code above to the function.

After you’ve added all the four lines of code, your withdrawToken() function should be the same as the code in ‘Working code’.

Step 8: Auction.sol - withdrawFunds()
The code in withdrawFunds() is very similar to that of withdrawToken(). Essentially, instead of transferring the token to the auction creator, it’ll transfer the funds to the auction creator.  Similar to withdrawToken(), this function is called when the auction ends or a direct buy happens. The code has already been added in for you, so you don’t need to add anything in for this step!
Step 9: Auction.sol - cancelAuction()
Moving on, we have the withdrawFunds() function. This function allows the auction creator to cancel an existing auction. We will be filling in the code for this function!
Similar to before, we’ll start by defining some conditions that are required before the function can proceed. The requirements we’ll be defining are:
  • only the auction creator can cancel the auction
  • auction state must still be open
  • auction cannot be cancelled if there is an existing bid

// 1) Only the auction creator can cancel the auction require(msg.sender == creator); // 2) The auction must be open require(getAuctionState() == AuctionState.OPEN);  // 3) The auction must not be cancelled if there is a bid require(maxBid == 0);

Again, we’ll be using the require keyword to specify these conditions. Add the code above inside the cancelAuction() function. 

// 4) Set auction to cancelled state to true isCancelled = true;  // 5) Transfer the NFT token to the auction creator _nft.transferFrom(address(this), creator, tokenId); // 6) Emit Auction Cancelled event emit AuctionCancelled();

After the conditions are met, we can set the isCancelled variable to true. Then we can proceed to transfer the NFT token back to the original owner. Lastly, we call and emit the AuctionCancelled event. Add the code above to your function.

If you’ve added the two chunks of code correctly, your cancelAuction() function should be the same as the code in ‘Working code’.
Working code
  function cancelAuction() external returns (bool) {     // 1) Only the auction creator can cancel the auction     require(msg.sender == creator);     // 2) The auction must be open     require(getAuctionState() == AuctionState.OPEN);      // 3) The auction must not be cancelled if there is a bid     require(maxBid == 0);     // 4) Set auction to cancelled state to true     isCancelled = true;      // 5) Transfer the NFT token to the auction creator     _nft.transferFrom(address(this), creator, tokenId);     // 6) Emit Auction Cancelled event     emit AuctionCancelled();      return true;   }
Step 10: Auction.sol - getAuctionState()
Now we’re on to the last function in Auction.sol - getAuctionState()! It is a simple function that returns the auction’s state based on the variables defined. We will be writing the code for this function. 
if(isCancelled) return AuctionState.CANCELLED;

Firstly, we check if the auction is cancelled. If it is, the function will return the state CANCELLED. Add the code above to getAuctionState(). If the syntax of this if statement looks strange to you, you'll be pleased to know that Solidity allows for single line if statements, making coding more efficient! This is just a bit of syntactic sugar to make your code look neater.

if(isDirectBuy) return AuctionState.DIRECT_BUY;

We do the same if an auction has been ended by a direct buy. Add the code above to your function as well.

if(block.timestamp >= endTime) return AuctionState.ENDED;

If the block timestamp is greater than the end timestamp declared, then return the state ENDED. Add the code above to your function.

return AuctionState.OPEN;

If all conditions above are false, the auction state OPEN is returned. Add the code above to your function. 

And we’re done with the edits needed for the Auction smart contract!
Step 11: AuctionManager.sol - An Overview
Next, let’s look at the other smart contract in our project - AuctionManager.sol. This contract is used to list all auctions and to create new auctions. In the same contracts folder, open up the AuctionManager.sol file. 

In AuctionManager.sol, we start off by importing the Auction.sol file as seen in line 4 of the file. As covered in earlier quests, the reason for importing other smart contracts is so that we are able to use objects, variables and functions defined in another smart contract.


We declare two variables at the start of the smart contract. The first variable is _auctionIdCounter, which is used as a counter to get the number of auctions created and assigns a new id when an auction is being created. 

The second variable is a mapping. In Solidity, a mapping is a table of keys and values. It is similar to arrays but follows a slightly different syntax. Mappings in Solidity acts like a hashtable or dictionary in other programming languages. Refer here for more information on mappings.

In line 8, we create a variable auctions with a key of uint type and a value pointing to an Auction. The Auction variable references the variables in the Auction.sol file.
Step 12: AuctionManager.sol - createAuction()

Now let's take a look at our first function in the smart contract - createAuction(). This function takes in 6 parameters, _nftAddress is of type address and the rest of the variables are of type uint. We also declare some conditions needed before this function can proceed.

These have already been added in for you so not to worry. Where we’ll be focusing on is the body of this function. 

uint auctionId = _auctionIdCounter;

First, we’ll declare an auctionId variable, this is used as an identifier for each auction. Then we get the current value of the counter and assign it to the variable. The auction counter is used to count and keep track of the number of auctions created in order to assign a unique id every time a new auction is to be created. Add the code above after the require statements.

_auctionIdCounter++;

We then increment the counter by 1 so that a new auction id is created. Add the code above to the function.

Auction auction = new Auction(msg.sender, _endTime, _minIncrement, _directBuyPrice, _startPrice, _nftAddress, _tokenId);

Next, we will create a new Auction contract instance using the parameters. The Auction keyword references the constructor() function in Auction.sol. Add the code above to your function.

IERC721 _nftToken = IERC721(_nftAddress);   _nftToken.transferFrom(msg.sender, address(auction), _tokenId);   auctions[auctionId] = auction;

Next, we’ll need to get the NFT token from the user’s wallet. With the wallet address obtained, we can now send it over to the Auction smart contract address to hold using the .transferFrom() function. Lastly, we add the auction we just created into the list of existing auctions. The Auction contract holds the token until the Auction is over or if a direct buy is triggered by a bidder. Add the code above to your function.

After adding in all the code listed above, your createAuction() function should look similar to the code in ‘Working code.
Working code
  function createAuction(     uint _endTime,     uint _minIncrement,     uint _directBuyPrice,     uint _startPrice,     address _nftAddress,     uint _tokenId   ) external returns (bool) {     require(_directBuyPrice > 0); // direct buy price must be greater than 0     require(_startPrice < _directBuyPrice); // start price is smaller than direct buy price     require(_endTime > 5 minutes); // end time must be greater than 5 minutes (setting it to 5 minutes for testing you can set it to 1 days or anything you would like)     // 1) get the current value of the counter     uint auctionId = _auctionIdCounter;     // 2) increment the counter     _auctionIdCounter++;     // 3) create the auction     Auction auction = new Auction(msg.sender, _endTime, _minIncrement, _directBuyPrice, _startPrice, _nftAddress, _tokenId);     // 4) get the nft token     IERC721 _nftToken = IERC721(_nftAddress);      // 5) transfer the token to the auction     _nftToken.transferFrom(msg.sender, address(auction), _tokenId);     // 6) add the auction to the map     auctions[auctionId] = auction;     return true;   }
Step 13: AuctionManager.sol - getAuctions()
Now let’s look at the getAuctions() function.


This function is used to return a list of auction addresses. Firstly, an array variable _auctions is instantiated with its length equal to the current value of the counter. Then, we use a for loop to iterate over the auctions mapping to populate _auctions. Lastly, the function returns this array.﻿

Finally, the last function is getAuctionInfo(). The code for this function might seem very long but essentially, all this function does is it obtains the information regarding the auctions.
Let's break the code down into smaller segments to help you understand it. 


The function takes in one argument, _auctionsList, which is an array of addresses. Our function will return the information regarding an auction - this is reflection in lines 54 to 60 in the image above.


The next few lines of code are for declaring array variables. The owner variable is of type address while the rest of the variables are of type uint. The size of all the arrays are set to the length of the _auctionsList array variable that was passed into the function. 


Then, we create a for loop and and assign the data in the variables accordingly based on the variables declared in Auction.sol.


Lastly, we return the arrays that we just populated. And we’re done!﻿
